  "style": "IEEE",
  "texts": [
    "It is frequently suggested that CoPilot produces unique coding suggestions based on what it learned from this training data, rather than directly copying any existing code, and that those prompting CoPilot are the sole owners of the outputs [19,24,48].",
    "It is unclear, however, if this is the case.",
    "Many authors of code used for training have disagreed, for example, insisting that CoPilot fails to use appropriate attribution for licensed code.",
    "It appears, by GitHub's internal testing, that CoPilot plagiarizes about 1% of the time, and even when not exactly replicating existing code it has been shown to provide solutions to specific problems with outputs highly similar to existing, licensed code [24,25].",
    "While many predict that this may turn out to be deemed 'fair use' in the various lawsuits brought against GitHub, such an approach goes against existing, socially agreed upon attribution standards in the coding community where the misappropriation of coding ideas or solutions is disapproved of, even while cooperative copy-pasting is customary."
  ],
